BOVINE TUBERCULOSIS - FRANCE: (NOUVELLE-AQUITAINE) CATTLE, SPREAD, DORDOGNE
***************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 12 Oct 2021 1:58 PM
Source: Tellerreport [edited]
https://www.tellerreport.com/life/2021-10-12-two-new-variants-of-bovine-tuberculosis-detected-in-dordogne.SJypnrmSt.html


Two new variants [see comment] and 27 outbreaks of bovine tuberculosis (bTB) were detected in Dordogne during the 2020-2021 surveillance campaign, making this department the territory most affected by this disease in France.

The Dordogne represents nearly a third of the 93 bTB outbreaks in France. Of the herds infected this year [2021] in the department, 15 were completely slaughtered and 12 partially.

bTB is an animal disease transmissible to humans (zoonosis), caused by bacteria [_Mycobacterium bovis_].

This bacterium can infect many species of ruminants, domestic and wild (mainly cattle and deer), but also wild boars, badgers and foxes. To avoid any risk for humans, the veterinary services carry out a systematic inspection of animals after slaughter.

When an outbreak is discovered in a farm, all the animals concerned are slaughtered and then cleaning and disinfection operations are carried out before restocking the herds.

In difference with the specific human tuberculosis [caused by _Mycobacterium tuberculosis_], presenting inter-human transmission which is mainly pulmonary, bTB - when transmitted from animals to humans - presents "in 80% of cases, extra-pulmonary localization; in particular, renal", explains the Ministry of Agriculture on its website.

