Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It will be interesting to obtain information on the 2 "variants" mentioned, in particular data indicative of the origin (eg. badgers, wild boar), transmission and spread of the pathogen(s).

Information on the techniques applied for differentiation of strains inside each species belonging to the _M. tuberculosis complex_, including _M. bovis_, and distinguishing _M. bovis from _M. tuberculosis_, is available in chapter 3.4.6. of OIE's Terrestrial Manual (https://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/3.04.06_BOVINE_TB.pdf; see page 1063).

_M. bovis_ has been identified in humans in most countries where isolates of mycobacteria from human patients have been fully characterised. The incidence of pulmonary tuberculosis caused by _M. bovis_ is higher in farm and slaughterhouse workers than in urban inhabitants. The transmission of _M. bovis_ to humans via milk and its products is eliminated by the pasteurisation of milk. One of the results of bTB eradication programmes has been a reduction in disease and death caused by bTB in the human population.

Although cattle are considered to be the true hosts of _M. bovis_, the disease has been reported in many domesticated and nondomesticated animals. - Mod.AS

